909. Salud Colect. 2015 Sep;11(3):411-21. doi: 10.1590/S1851-82652015000300008.

[Level of and change in road traffic mortality in Argentina, Chile, Colombia and 
Mexico, 2000-2011].

[Article in Spanish]

Escanés G(1), Agudelo-Botero M(2), Cardona D(3).

Author information:
(1)Universidad Nacional de Córdoba, Consejo Nacional de Investigaciones 
Científicas y Técnicas, Córdoba, Argentina.
(2)Instituto Nacional de Geriatría, México.
(3)Facultad de Medicina, Universidad CES, Medellín, Colombia.

The aim of this study was to estimate the effect of run-over fatalities and 
traffic collisions in life expectancy in Argentina, Chile, Colombia and Mexico, 
between 2000 and 2011. Years of life expectancy lost (YLEL) were calculated for 
the periods 2000-2002 and 2009-2011. The results show that road traffic deaths 
made up between 1% and 4% of all deaths in each country. In the first period, 
the highest level of mortality occurred in Colombia (YLEL=0.96) and the lowest 
in Argentina (YLEL=0.59). In all the countries studied except Argentina, the 
impact of these deaths on life expectancy was reduced in the second period. The 
main change took place in Colombia, reaching 0.72 YLEL in the second period. It 
is concluded that traffic-related deaths have a negative impact on health 
systems, victims, the productive sector, and society in general. From this point 
of view, the issue of road transit must be considered a matter of public health, 
requiring multi-sector intervention in the design of national and regional 
policies.

