that no competing interests exist.


919. Soc Sci Med. 2015 Nov;145:115-9. doi: 10.1016/j.socscimed.2015.09.020. Epub
2015  Sep 18.

Happiness and longevity in the United States.

Lawrence EM(1), Rogers RG(2), Wadsworth T(2).

Author information:
(1)University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, United States. Electronic address: 
lizlaw@unc.edu.
(2)University of Colorado Boulder, United States.

This is the first study to our knowledge to examine the relationship between 
happiness and longevity among a nationally representative sample of adults. We 
use the recently-released General Social Survey-National Death Index dataset and 
Cox proportional hazards models to reveal that overall happiness is related to 
longer lives among U.S. adults. Indeed, compared to very happy people, the risk 
of death over the follow-up period is 6% (95% CI 1.01-1.11) higher among 
individuals who are pretty happy and 14% (95% CI 1.06-1.22) higher among those 
who are not happy, net of marital status, socioeconomic status, census division, 
and religious attendance. This study provides support for happiness as a 
stand-alone indicator of well-being that should be used more widely in social 
science and health research.

